{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"gutenberg-press-1440","type":"event","content":{"title":"Gutenberg's Printing Press","date_label":"c. 1440","description":"Around **1440**, **Johannes Gutenberg** of Mainz developed the first movable-type printing press in Europe, producing his famous **42-line Bible** (the Gutenberg Bible) around 1455.\n\nThe printing press was arguably the most transformative technology of the second millennium. Before Gutenberg, a single scribe might take a year to copy one book; a press could produce hundreds of copies in days. The result was an explosion in the availability of written knowledge, the standardization of languages, the spread of literacy, and the erosion of the Church's monopoly on information.\n\nWithin fifty years of Gutenberg's invention, over **twenty million books** had been printed in Europe. The press made the **Protestant Reformation** possible by allowing Luther's ideas to spread faster than the Church could suppress them, enabled the **Scientific Revolution** by circulating findings across borders, and planted the seeds of the Enlightenment.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["gutenberg","printing-press","media","literacy","reformation","1440","information"],"sources":[{"title":"Johannes Gutenberg — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Johannes-Gutenberg"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1440","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":960,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"global"}}}
